No but largely depends on the course. Only courses I could think of that have large projects are 162 (operating systems), 161 (security), and 164 (compilers).

I think the CS61B projects were by far the least time-consuming/easiest programming projects I've dealt with across 170/188/189.

------

188 projects are comparable to 61A projects in that they're fill-in-the-blank, guided projects (but that does not necessarily mean they're easy).

189 doesn't really have projects like 61B. It's a theory-based class, so it revolves around mathematical proofs and problem sets, with some coding.

From what I hear, 184 projects are actually quite time-consuming.

children.subject: Yeah, I took this last year. Honestly, this class was the most fun I've had on any projects in my time at Berkeley. A large part of how long a project takes is how we perceive working on it - I felt like the 194-26 projects were pretty quick because they were so fun (and visual). In reality, it was a couple of days working intermittently (in the evenings) on them to finish each one. Didn't feel overwhelming.
Does anyone know anything about CS194-26 and how time consuming this one is?

history.content:
For example, do projects in CS184, CS188, CS189 take a long time to finish? Are they as in-depth as CS61B? If so, which combination do you recommend against? 

I don't want overwhelming semesters .
